MIDTERM PROJECT DELIVERABLES

BUSINESS UNDERSTANDING¶

The question we are trying to answer is how can we tell the greatness of the movie before is it released in cinema. With all the time it takes to aquire an appropriate and reasonable amount of critics to review a movie after is it released, we want to find a faster and easier way to tell predict a movies success.

  • the goal of this project is to predict movie success.

data to include would include

  • country released in
  • year move is released
  • movie popularity on social media
  • director popularity on social media
  • top 3 actors/actresses social media popularity

-duration is the only variables that is strongly correlated with imdb_score that is kept in the data

def label_aspect_ratio(x):
   if x < 1.80:
      return 1
   if x < 1.85:
      return 2
   if x < 2.00:
      return 3
   if x < 2.30:
      return 4
   return 5

df1['aspect_ratio_groups'] = df1['aspect_ratio'].apply(label_aspect_ratio)

Summary¶

Summary The variable most highly correlated with imdb score is duration; the longer the movie the higher the rating. movies < 8 tend to be near the mean of duration. The next highest correlated is budget; a high budget does not mean a successful movie. Third is director popularity, this could be caused because of director and audience relationships. People seem to like how a specific director makes movies over another. Though, the graph shows that some highly accredited directors are not well known on facebook and some popular facebook directors have bad movies.

Other varibales that are correlated to each other would include title_year and color; the later the movie came out the more likely it is to be in color. title_year is also highly correlated to rating category PG-13; the later the movie came out the more likely it is to be PG-13.

Actor_3_facebook_likes and actor_2_facebook_likes are highly correlated as well. This could be because of actor 1 historically has the significantly high popularity compared to actor 2 and 3.

overall, It is still extremely hard to consistently predict the success of a movie not yet released. There are some strong and important correlations but none that are definitive.

STORYTELLING: technical and managerial implications and suggestions (for business people/investors)

  • After running multiple feature selection models my data showed that Recursive Feature Model has the lowest MSE score. The variables chosen were: aspect_ratio, facenumber_in_poster, title_year, and duration. To double check my data I ran both my output for selectKbest and RFE in two different linear regression models. The output from that data shows that the variables selected in RFE are more fitted for this project than selectKbest.

  • Based off the data my recommendations would be to have a focus on aspect_ration. Most viewers wont necessarily know what it is or what is does but can tell a difference between the quality of the picture in relationship to sizing on the screen. Lastly, marketing seems to have a large impact on viewers and ratings. Management should spend more time on marketing the movies, like posters.

  • Another variable that could be added is the time of year, seasonality can shift views preference of a movie, for example a Christmas movie will receive higher scores around Christmas time than during the summer Another variable that might be important is the soundtrack and who produces it. Music can make or break a movie.
